class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/rockland-inc.com\/store\/Water-and-Molecular-Biology-Solutions-MB-008-O4L_23106.aspx\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Rockland, MB-008<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">). Centrifuge for 2 min at RT, 180 xg. Aspirate the supernatant.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">3.<\/span><span> Add <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> of warm (<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> ) 0.05% Trypsin (<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.thermofisher.com\/order\/catalog\/product\/25300054#\/25300054\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Invitrogen, 25300054<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">) to the islets. Pipette up and down with p1000.\u00a0<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">4<\/span><span>. Incubate at <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> for 9 min, or until cells are in single cells. Pipette up and down at t=7 min, 4 min, 2 min, 0 min.\u00a0<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">5.<\/span><span> Stop the trypsin reaction by adding <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> of 100% FBS (<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.fishersci.com\/shop\/products\/hyclone-fetal-bovine-serum-usda-tested-5\/SH3091003\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Hyclone, SH3091003<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">) to the dissociated islets and pass cells through BD FACs tube with strainer top (<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/ecatalog.corning.com\/life-sciences\/b2c\/US\/en\/General-Labware\/Tubes\/Tubes,-Round-Bottom\/Falcon%C2%AE-Round-Bottom-Polystyrene-Tubes\/p\/352235\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Corning 352235<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">)<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">6.<\/span><span> Use <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> of 100% FBS to rinse the tube and pass through the strainer.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">7.<\/span><span> Transfer cells to <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> conical. Centrifuge 4 min, 400 xg.\u00a0<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">8.<\/span><span> Remove the supernatant and wash cells with PBS with 10% FBS. Centrifuge for 4 min, 400 xg.\u00a0<\/span><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">9.<\/span><span> Wash the cells with PBS with 10% FBS and centrifuge for 4 min, 400 xg. Remove the supernatant.<\/span><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">10.<\/span><span> Count cells using a countess chamber.<\/span><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">11.<\/span><span> For the scATACseq, do the final resuspension in 0.04%\u00a0BSA in PBS as is consistent with the instructions for using fresh cell in the Nuclei Isolation Protocol.<\/span><\/div><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"D73EA410DE8711EBA9591D6A70173A42","order_id":2,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":15,"unit":"mL","title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"EAF8B090DE8711EBA9591D6A70173A42","order_id":3,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":10,"unit":"mL","title":""}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"12124D80DE8811EBA9591D6A70173A42","order_id":4,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":1,"unit":"mL","title":""}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"18A5A700DE8811EBA9591D6A70173A42","order_id":5,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":37,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054729,"guid":"3EC79D80DE8811EBA9591D6A70173A42","order_id":6,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":37,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054730,"guid":"4F460700DE8811EBA9591D6A70173A42","order_id":7,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":1,"unit":"mL","title":""}},{"id":1054731,"guid":"862BFB80DE8811EBA9591D6A70173A42","order_id":8,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":1,"unit":"mL","title":""}},{"id":1054732,"guid":"96E52410DE8811EBA9591D6A70173A42","order_id":9,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":15,"unit":"mL","title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1209002,"guid":"FD94FB90DE8811EBA9591D6A70173A42","previous_id":1208999,"previous_guid":"C34FCBF0DE8711EBA9591D6A70173A42","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"684465A7F9C047C2A94CE7E8B9BD4727","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Links to kits used in post-processing"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"9C1A048F2A9D4647BBEC2ABF0EB47A2B","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">1.<\/span><span> For nuclei isolation the protocol used is: <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/assets.ctfassets.net\/an68im79xiti\/5g035d2ngCW1aB9DFqPphO\/71445a59fb282ea273a866c26cb5d319\/CG000169_DemonstratedProtocol_NucleiIsolation_ATAC_Sequencing_RevD.pdf\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Nuclei Isolation for Single Cell ATAC Sequencing<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">. We target a 5000 nuclei recovery for this protocol.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">2.<\/span><span> Samples are processed for scATAC seq using <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/assets.ctfassets.net\/an68im79xiti\/4dXLdjCzh5xKBlgRBkfSmW\/eb0b5b463ced5778fa68e7dc50829e50\/CG000168_ChromiumSingleCell_ATAC_ReagentKits_UserGuide_RevD.pdf\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Chromium Single Cell ATAC Reagent Kits<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Interrogating cell-type specific chromatin accessibility can reveal cis-regulatory elements linked to downstream gene expression patterns. Assay for Transposase-Accessible Chromatin using Sequencing (ATAC-Seq) is a technique that assays genome-wide chromatin accessibility and can reveal nucleosome positioning patterns, map enhancer and promoter regions, or reveal transcription factor binding sites. Single-cell Assay for Transposase-Accessible Chromatin using Sequencing (scATAC-seq) adapts the bulk ATAC-sequencing protocol to separate individual nuclei and assay chromatin state with single-cell resolution. This technique allows for resolution of gene accessibility patterns within specific pancreatic cell types such as \u03b1-cells, \u03b2-cells, and acinar cells.<\/span><span><\/span><\/div><br\/><br\/><br\/><\/div>","changed_on":1628783992}